Main points

Intro to Buddhist Meditation

Meditation is the way the individual frees him or herself from distractions and from the limitations imposed by the self. As such, it has no ethical value in itself  it is a means to an end.

Through meditation, we can use emotions such as anger, greed and hatred in order to first recognise and then overcome them

The ultimate aim of meditation is the achievement of Nirvana, when all desire has been eliminated.

Vipassana meditation is on the oneness of all things. In order to realise this state it is essential to meditate on the difference between appearance and reality  things that appear separate are not. Even my body is not mine, we are part of a deeper unity. This leads to compassion for all things.

Monk meditating

Note the position of the fingers. This is a standard position and is intended to help focus when sitting with a straight back and breathing correctly. If the thumbs rise, it is an indication of too much tension, whilst if they fall it signals a lack of concentration.

The aim of the Buddhist life is to become free of the cycle of Samsara (i.e. of the cycle of birth and death). This can only be done by achieving enlightenment through meditation.

The farmer and the cow

We must train the mind as a farmer trains his cow. The cow is our thinking. The farmer is the meditator. The mind is like the cow who wants to eat the wheat harvest. When you tend a cow, you let it go free but you keep watch over it. You put a fence around the field,. If it goes too close to the wheat fields, you restrain it with a the fence. The mind is like this, it needs to be trained. (The Dhammapada)

Nirvana or Nibbana

The word Nirvana or Nibbana means be extinguished or blown out like the flame of a candle. This seems to imply that Nirvana is the same as being extinguished. But this is mistaken.

What is blown out is the desire, NOT the person. Something remains but since all that pertains to the self is extinguished it is not easy to define what this is. The unlimited truth about reality, independent of time, space and change, remains even after our selfish ego is destroyed and this is the supreme goal of Buddhists.

There are different schools in Buddhism about Nirvana (as there are different schools of Christian thought about heaven).

Views on Nirvana

The Vaibhashika school maintains that when Nirvana is achieved, there is no more consciousness and no more being. However if this is the case, then there is no being to achieve it and the Buddha, in achieving Nirvana, ceases to exist.

The Dalai Lama denies that Nirvana is nothingness and says that it is the complete purified state of mind from which all negative thoughts and emotions have been removed. It is the ultimate nature of mind.

To say that (a) the nature of Nirvana is inexpressible or (b) the nature of the identity of the individual in Nirvana is inexpressible, is NOT the same as denying there is any individuality. This issue is left open  as the Buddha desired to do when dealing with metaphysical questions.

The Buddha taught that life is like being trapped in a burning building  the only way out to escape the cycle of birth and death is to become enlightened.

Samatha

Samatha is a Buddhist term that is often translated as the "tranquility of the mind". Originally, samatha was developed by abiding in the jhanas, but the later Buddhist tradition also re-introduced single-pointed meditation, which includes a variety of mind-calming techniques, as a means to develop calm.
